Development of travel prices since 1989
By 1989 there were only five state travel agencies approved in the ČSSR: Čedok, sports tourist, CKM, recrea and car tourist.
The travel agencies sold only travels to the socialist Eastern Block countries at the time, in which western only were allowed to choose.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the East Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia entered a pro-west course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Block (also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise it was not possible to travel individually.
The travel agencies also offered travel in the west, but then they had to buy huge snakes or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
The matter hadn't been done for a long time.
The so-called "politically reliable" people - the condition for a trip to the West - were only granted - the others were not allowed to travel.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to use the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, most of the Czechs spent their vacation in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought numerous weekend houses and dates - a habit that lasts until today.
The total revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czech Republic.
While a holiday in the DDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their abroad holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that it was not possible to travel to the most popular country of the Czech Republic until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
As from the beginning of the 1990s of the past century, the exchange obligation was repealed into the neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could simply not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech vacationers slept in the park in Paris when traveling to Paris, because who would already have had the money for a accommodation in the hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature in foreign travels from Czechs was then a suitcase packed with conserves, beer and permanent worst, etc..
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown – after decades our tourists were finally able to purchase the western currency freely.
Our level of life and thereby also the average salaries increased, which in 1997 called in another important moment.
Thanks to increased demands for travel, the travel agencies began regularly to prepare travel through charter flights after 1997, thus allowing flights to negotiate quantity discounts incrediblely compared to the past.
In the late 1990s, with the exception of the United States, the Czechs had already had bankrupt payment traffic with all the high-developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of the "post-general" travel was made in 2000 when, thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, every year, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been operated in far-distance sunny countries; in this year, they are directly flying from Czech Republic twelve exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd Czechs travels every year to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States took up the visa obligation for Czech tourists, which definitely brought our country into the high-developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs first spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spending more than 15 Tsd CZK per head for a single holiday stay, including the costs at the vacation site.
