Climate contradictions in the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in the government, unemployment and black work grew in Sinaloa, while foreign investments went down and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, the economic history of Sinaloa will remain in mind. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and gives rise to great hopes regarding economic growth, is at the government. However, as a result of climate disputes, growth cannot be spoken of, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators have worsened.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in millions of agriculture, but also engraved the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity in the first quarter, with 3.6 per cent. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 per cent, which broke its impact on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (i.e. the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agriculture) about the impact of frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural property are damaged, of which 78.03% were perfect and the rest of 21,07% were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has continued to increase unemployment in the Mexican State. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía has observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, since 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa did not have employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the employment population. In the second quarter, unemployment rates increased to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting from 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa. These are 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year depends on several factors. The economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dekan of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments on the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, it is not easy to allow them to work for themselves, to invest or to use it for anything else to combat money laundering in the Congress," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country on looking for work in abroad, especially in the United States, has declined. This is due to the problems of entry and, on the one hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here that makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when taking into account the high share of black work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38% of the employees in the country who are working without paying into the social insurance cash.
Employment and black labour are the lowest wages in all Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Authority for Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September; this is much less than the total state average of 7375 pesos.
Decline of the ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the growing unemployment, in 2011 the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the past ten years is recorded. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority) the ADI was $630.597 from January to June, which is 87.74 per cent in comparison to $5.43.312 in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) represents an overall investment of 17.280 000 pesos in 2011, which is mainly originating from companies from the Tertiary sector.
The debts
In view of the economic crisis, the national government in July applied for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship, Mario López Valdés' government inability was revealed in the first year of government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Processing Industry in Mexico), represented that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very necessarily this year. It has to be worked hard to recover the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we have to work twice. The efforts of all the government teams that have already been well agreed have not been sufficiently coordinated," he explained.
Slow economic development
Loredo López stated that events, such as the frost at the beginning of the year, made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slowing economy that is not in motion enough to create an economic dynamic that could create a acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore we will conclude the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine calling
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Company of Mexico) in Sinaloa, declared that the State should be motivated to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general we have seen that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme for redetermining the economic calling and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that leads the government's efforts to better railways.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has come forward, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he explained.
He stressed that the current government power has made progress in the government.
"There are areas that can be said that the government has acted more extensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
