Asphalt by UNAM prevents holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico, UNAM developed polymer-modified asphalts to make the mix more resistant to the weather conditions and temperature variations
If the rainy time in the zone Metropolitana del Valle de México (the city area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nahjera, researcher at the University of UNAM, would not need to repair nearly 200 000 holes, warning and assured that if the interpretation and maintenance of the asphalt stock were adequately achieved, the number of holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "technical holes", which he held on the basis of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, which, however, has a greater mechanical resistance both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahjera believed that this type of modified asphalts in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, should be used to improve the behaviour of the road crew and thus avoid the occurrence of holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most severe part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon link of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called maltene. Together, they give the road stock its characteristic tealastic behavior.
Asphalt sealing means that at high temperatures of nearly 180°C it acts like a liquid, at 120°C it is very volatile and almost fixed at 50°C, while it becomes broken at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not equal, but changes on one day in dependency on the conditions and temperature variations," the chemical engineer concluded.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road cover, which consisted of six material layers, of which the last three asphalts included.
Between the upper layers, there is a layer of asphalt, which is bathed from small, asphalt and then consists of solid stones.
Each single stone of this sleeve was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of powers in the road coating.
"If it was modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"About the sliding layer," he concluded, "the last layer is designed, which is known as a cargo layer consisting of small stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle rippes, they need a greater mechanical force than the sliding layer and it has to repair.
The main forces of this road coating are received and distributed, the cargo layer also needs a proper thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially moisture and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to be taken into account, above all the water," he said, "for it significantly affects the behavior of the sliding layer.
When the site is moist, water penetrates into the layer and comes out difficultly. This causes a rise in all layers of the road coating and consequently the occurrence of holes.
When a slaughter hole arises," he said, "it will first be carried off the cover, while the sliding layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained in the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Lastema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico’s National Research System) stated that vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of holes. Therefore, the thickness of any layer of the road carriage must always be in proportion to vehicle load and it must be ensured that this system is respected to avoid frequent holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research was still waiting, for example about asphalt emulsions that were already on the market in other countries, with which the holes were easily and without use of high temperatures.
